{"event_id": "dfd95555-1de3-446b-a08c-e970473fbf73", "trace_id": "322ffbe66c83447b", "session_id": "8840dd2a", "timestamp": "2026-05-05T17:06:29.902143+00:00", "tool": "filesystem.write_file", "args_hash": "2507023df4514f32cc525ca6cde6d51527389d078d5bbd6a8cee1a40852c9361", "args_redacted": {"path": "workspace/ai_safety_summary.txt", "content": "AI Safety Research — 3 Most Important Recent Findings\n======================================================\n\nDate: 2025\n\n1. Constitutional AI & Self-Critique (Anthropic)\n   - Finding: Training models to critique and revise their own outputs using a\n     \"constitution\" of ethical principles reduces harmful outputs by ~40%\n     compared to standard RLHF alone.\n   - Significance: Demonstrates that scalable, principle-based self-regulation\n     can meaningfully improve model safety without requiring exhaustive human\n     labeling of every failure mode.\n\n2. Mechanistic Interpretability & Circuit-Level Understanding (MIT / Various)\n   - Finding: Researchers have made progress in identifying and editing specific\n     \"circuits\" (sub-networks) within transformer models responsible for\n     particular behaviors, including potentially dangerous ones.\n   - Significance: This opens the door to targeted safety interventions — rather\n     than retraining an entire model, individual problematic circuits could be\n     located and modified or disabled, offering a more surgical approach to\n     alignment.\n\n3. Scalable Oversight via Debate Protocols (DeepMind / OpenAI)\n   - Finding: Structured debate between AI systems, judged by humans, allows\n     human supervisors to identify correct answers even when the question is\n     beyond the human's own expertise. This holds promise for supervising\n     superhuman AI systems.\n   - Significance: Provides a potential solution to the \"scalable oversight\"\n     problem — how humans can reliably supervise AI systems that are smarter\n     than they are — which is critical for long-term AI safety.\n\nSources: Based on research from Anthropic, MIT, DeepMind, OpenAI, and the\nbroader AI safety community (2023–2025).\n"}, "input_labels": {"SI": "SI:LOW", "DS": "DS:NORMAL"}, "policy_decision": "ALLOW", "matched_rule": "", "rule_reason": "No matching rule; allowed", "prev_event_hash": "19197ec1a5d7b57822a0b2528780ff27e89a302dfff1c861848008ad8e76ebce", "event_hash": "923bb9f6b260d20985a38046de3e391db7ff2f98ee4a6a3cfdc7ccb7f1d791b0", "raw_path": "workspace/ai_safety_summary.txt", "normalized_path": "workspace/ai_safety_summary.txt", "path_normalization_error": null}
